The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      The City Diary
                Three members of a Salt Lake family were diagnosed with chikungunya on Wednesday. Nilotpal Roy, 40, his wife Supriya, 35, and daughter Tanurima, 13, had been suffering from high fever since last week. Blood test reports confirmed the disease on Wednesday. Medical officers of Bidhannagar Municipality visited the familys Purbachal Cluster XI home in the afternoon. These are the first cases of chikungunya in Salt Lake this season. Symptoms of the disease include high fever, joint pains and weakness. The viral fever lasts five to seven days. Symptomatic treatment could easily cure the disease, said doctors.     State chief secretary Samar Ghosh met governor M.K. Narayanan at Raj Bhavan on Wednesday afternoon. Writers Buildings officials said the meeting was about the states financial problems, which have been in the news recently. Ghosh declined comment. Five days back, finance minister Asim Dasgupta met the governor to get his signature on the ordinance that enabled the state government to hike the VAT on luxury and some non-essential items by 1 per cent.    N. Vishwanathan, 80, a retired teacher of English at St Xaviers College and an actor, died in his south Calcutta home on Wednesday night. He was a diabetic and had been in and out of hospital for the past three months. Vishwanathan had acted in over 50 Bengali films, including Satyajit Rays Kanchenjungha, and in films in other languages. His last screen appearance was in Gumshuda, directed by his son Ashoke. St Xaviers College pays its respect. He was an efficient professor and the college will miss him, said principal Father Felix Raj. He was one of those who kept his closeness to the school and the college. He was a product of both. He was a great teacher and a sought-after orator, said Father P.C. Mathew, a former principal of St Xaviers College.    A fire broke out on the ground floor electric meter room of a five-storey residential-cum-commercial complex at Banstala in Burrabazar on Wednesday evening. Five tenders doused the flames in an hour.    Bapi Halder, Tarun Maity, Mickey Singh and Sanatan Goswami, in their 20s, were arrested near Ruby Hospital on Wednesday evening while they were allegedly on their way to commit a robbery. A pipegun with a bullet, four bombs and a dagger were found on them.     Sisir Saha, 34, who used to stay alone in a rented flat in Liluahs Chokpara was found dead on Wednesday.                                                                                                                                               
